---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const allSoftware = await getCollection('software');
const ketamineSpecific = allSoftware.filter(
  (s) =>
    s.data.ketamine_features.iv_protocols ||
    s.data.ketamine_features.im_protocols ||
    s.data.ketamine_features.ketamine_consent_forms
);

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'How to Choose an EHR for Your Ketamine Clinic',
  description: 'A comprehensive guide to evaluating EHR and practice management software for ketamine and psychedelic therapy practices.',
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Ketamine Software Directory',
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How to Choose an EHR for Your Ketamine Clinic | Buyer's Guide"
  description="A comprehensive guide to evaluating EHR and practice management software for ketamine and psychedelic therapy practices. Learn what features matter most."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="border-b border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 px-4 py-3 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm">
        <li>
          <a href="/" class="text-slate-500 hover:text-slate-700">Home</a>
        </li>
        <li class="text-slate-400">/</li>
        <li>
          <a href="/guides/" class="text-slate-500 hover:text-slate-700">Guides</a>
        </li>
        <li class="text-slate-400">/</li>
        <li class="text-slate-900">Choosing a Ketamine EHR</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- Article -->
  <article class="px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <!-- Header -->
      <header>
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl">
          How to Choose an EHR for Your Ketamine Clinic
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-600">
          A comprehensive guide to evaluating EHR and practice management software for ketamine and psychedelic therapy practices.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-slate-500">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated: January 2025</span>
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- Table of Contents -->
      <nav class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-6">
        <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900">Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm">
          <li><a href="#why-ketamine-specific" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">1. Why Ketamine-Specific Features Matter</a></li>
          <li><a href="#must-have-features" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">2. Must-Have Features</a></li>
          <li><a href="#nice-to-have" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">3. Nice-to-Have Features</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pricing-models" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">4. Understanding Pricing Models</a></li>
          <li><a href="#implementation" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">5. Implementation Considerations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#questions-to-ask" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">6. Questions to Ask Vendors</a></li>
          <li><a href="#recommendations" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">7. Our Recommendations</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <!-- Content -->
      <div class="prose prose-gray mt-12 max-w-none">
        <h2 id="why-ketamine-specific">Why Ketamine-Specific Features Matter</h2>
        <p>
          Running a ketamine clinic isn't like running a typical outpatient practice. You have unique workflow requirements that general-purpose EHRs weren't designed to handle:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Multi-session treatment series</strong> - Patients typically complete 4-6 initial infusions over 2-3 weeks, then maintenance sessions</li>
          <li><strong>Real-time vital monitoring</strong> - IV and IM administrations require documented vital sign tracking during sessions</li>
          <li><strong>Outcome measurement</strong> - Tracking PHQ-9, GAD-7, and other scales over time to demonstrate treatment efficacy</li>
          <li><strong>SPRAVATO® compliance</strong> - If you offer esketamine, you need REMS-compliant documentation workflows</li>
          <li><strong>Controlled substance handling</strong> - ePrescribing for Schedule III substances with PDMP integration</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          A general behavioral health EHR can work, but you'll spend significant time building custom templates and workarounds. A ketamine-specific solution saves that time and reduces compliance risk.
        </p>

        <h2 id="must-have-features">Must-Have Features</h2>
        <p>
          Regardless of which software you choose, ensure it includes these essential capabilities:
        </p>

        <h3>Clinical Documentation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ePrescribing for controlled substances (EPCS)</strong> - Essential for prescribing ketamine troches, nasal spray, or other take-home formulations</li>
          <li><strong>PDMP integration</strong> - Required in most states to check prescription drug monitoring databases</li>
          <li><strong>Customizable note templates</strong> - You'll need to document infusion protocols, vital signs, and patient responses</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Patient Rating Scales</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>PHQ-9</strong> - Depression severity</li>
          <li><strong>GAD-7</strong> - Anxiety severity</li>
          <li><strong>PCL-5</strong> - PTSD symptoms (if treating trauma patients)</li>
          <li><strong>Visual Analog Scale</strong> - Pain assessment (if treating chronic pain)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The best systems auto-score these assessments and graph trends over time.
        </p>

        <h3>Billing & Insurance</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Insurance claim submission</strong> - For practices billing insurance (note: many ketamine treatments are cash-pay)</li>
          <li><strong>Payment processing</strong> - Credit card integration for patient payments</li>
          <li><strong>Superbill generation</strong> - For patients seeking out-of-network reimbursement</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Compliance & Security</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>HIPAA compliance</strong> - Non-negotiable for any healthcare software</li>
          <li><strong>Audit trails</strong> - Documentation of who accessed what records and when</li>
          <li><strong>Secure messaging</strong> - Encrypted communication with patients</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="nice-to-have">Nice-to-Have Features</h2>
        <p>
          These features aren't essential but can significantly improve your workflow:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>IV/IM protocol templates</strong> - Pre-built documentation for ketamine infusions and injections</li>
          <li><strong>Treatment series tracking</strong> - Automatic scheduling and tracking of multi-session protocols</li>
          <li><strong>Ketamine-specific consent forms</strong> - Pre-built informed consent documents</li>
          <li><strong>Inventory tracking</strong> - Monitor ketamine stock levels and expiration dates</li>
          <li><strong>AI-assisted documentation</strong> - Auto-generate notes from session recordings</li>
          <li><strong>Integrated telehealth</strong> - For intake consultations and follow-ups</li>
          <li><strong>Patient portal</strong> - Self-service scheduling, paperwork, and messaging</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="pricing-models">Understanding Pricing Models</h2>
        <p>
          Healthcare software pricing varies significantly. Here's what to expect:
        </p>

        <h3>Per-Clinician Pricing</h3>
        <p>
          Most common model. You pay a monthly fee for each provider (MD, NP, PA) using the system. Typical range: $99-300/clinician/month.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Watch out for:</strong> Some vendors count nurse practitioners and physician assistants as full clinicians, significantly increasing costs.
        </p>

        <h3>Flat-Rate Pricing</h3>
        <p>
          A single monthly fee regardless of team size. Better for larger practices with multiple providers. Typical range: $200-500/month.
        </p>

        <h3>Per-Encounter Pricing</h3>
        <p>
          Pay based on how many patient encounters you bill. Good for low-volume practices or startups.
        </p>

        <h3>Hidden Costs to Ask About</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>ePrescribing add-on fees</li>
          <li>PDMP integration fees</li>
          <li>Implementation and training costs</li>
          <li>Data migration fees</li>
          <li>Text message reminder fees</li>
          <li>API access fees</li>
          <li>Additional user fees for staff</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="implementation">Implementation Considerations</h2>

        <h3>Data Migration</h3>
        <p>
          If you're switching from another EHR, ask about data migration. Some vendors include it; others charge thousands of dollars. Consider:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Can you export patient demographics, insurance info, and clinical notes?</li>
          <li>Will historical outcome measurements transfer?</li>
          <li>What's the timeline for migration?</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Training</h3>
        <p>
          Even "intuitive" software requires training. Ask:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Is training included in the subscription?</li>
          <li>Is it live or self-paced?</li>
          <li>What about training for new hires?</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Support</h3>
        <p>
          When something breaks on a busy clinic day, you need help fast. Compare:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Support hours (24/7 vs. business hours only)</li>
          <li>Support channels (phone, chat, email)</li>
          <li>Average response time</li>
          <li>US-based vs. offshore support</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="questions-to-ask">Questions to Ask Vendors</h2>
        <p>
          Before committing, ask these questions:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Do you have other ketamine clinics using your software? Can I speak with references?</li>
          <li>What ketamine-specific templates or workflows are included?</li>
          <li>How do you handle treatment series tracking and scheduling?</li>
          <li>Can I customize outcome measure questionnaires?</li>
          <li>What's included in the base price vs. add-ons?</li>
          <li>What's the contract length? Can I cancel monthly?</li>
          <li>Is there a free trial to evaluate before committing?</li>
          <li>How long does implementation typically take?</li>
          <li>What happens to my data if I leave?</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="recommendations">Our Recommendations</h2>
        <p>
          Based on our research, here's how we'd categorize the options:
        </p>

        <h3>Best for Ketamine-Only Practices</h3>
        <p>
          If ketamine therapy is your primary or only service, consider <strong>ketamine-specific</strong> solutions:
        </p>
        <ul>
          {ketamineSpecific.map((s) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`/software/${s.data.slug}/`} class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700">
                {s.data.name}
              </a>
              {' '}- {s.data.ideal_for}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>

        <h3>Best for Multi-Service Practices</h3>
        <p>
          If you offer ketamine alongside traditional psychiatry or therapy, a broader behavioral health EHR with strong customization may work better. Consider Valant, TherapyNotes, or PracticeQ.
        </p>

        <h3>Best for Budget-Conscious Startups</h3>
        <p>
          If you're just starting out and need to minimize costs, consider Charm Health (free tier available) or SimplePractice ($49/month starter plan).
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-teal-200 bg-teal-50 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Ready to Compare?</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
          Use our comparison tool to evaluate software options side-by-side.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/compare/"
          class="mt-4 inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-teal-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-teal-700"
        >
          Compare Software
          <svg class="ml-2 h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2" stroke="currentColor">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M13.5 4.5 21 12m0 0-7.5 7.5M21 12H3" />
          </svg>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
